    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-01-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-01-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="550"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d550">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">851.014/1415</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">President</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-01-24">January 24,
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum for the Secretary of State</hi>
                </p>
                <p>I saw <persName corresp="#p_HV1">Halifax</persName> last week and told him quite
                    frankly that it was perfectly true that I had, for over a year, expressed the
                    opinion that Indo-China should not go back to France but that it should be
                    administered by an international trusteeship.<note n="1" xml:id="d550fn1">The
                        substance of the remarks made by <persName corresp="#p_HV1"
                            >Halifax</persName> to <persName corresp="#p_HC1">Hull</persName> on
                        January 3, 1944 (see <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_864">p.
                            864</ref>), had been conveyed by <persName corresp="#p_HC1"
                            >Hull</persName> to <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName> in
                        a memorandum of January 14, 1944 (851.014/134a).</note> France has had the
                    country—thirty million inhabitants for nearly one hundred years, and the people
                    are worse off than they were at the beginning.</p>
                <p>As a matter of interest, I am wholeheartedly supported in this view by <gloss
                        target="#t_Generalissimo1">Generalissimo</gloss>
                    <persName corresp="#p_CKS1">Chiang Kai-shek</persName> and by Marshal <persName
                        corresp="#p_SIV1">Stalin</persName>.<note n="2" xml:id="d550fn2">See <hi
                            rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_325">pp. 325</ref>, <ref
                            target="#pg_485">485</ref>.</note> I see no reason to play in with the
                    British Foreign Office in this matter. The only reason they seem to oppose it is
                    that they fear the effect it would have on their own possessions and those of
                    the Dutch. They have never liked the idea of trusteeship because it is, in some
                    instances, <pb facs="0977" n="873" xml:id="pg_873"/> aimed at future
                    independence. This is true in the case of Indo-China.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">F[<hi rend="smallcaps">ranklin</hi>] D R[<hi
                                rend="smallcaps">oosevelt</hi>]</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
